harmonic functions, Wirtinger derivatives

Let Ω⊆C\Omega \subseteq \CΩ⊆C be a non-empty open connected set. If f ⁣:Ω→C\func{f}{\Omega}{\C}f:Ω→C is harmonic and f2f^2f2 is also harmonic, show that either fff or f‾\conj{f}f​ is holomorphic on Ω\OmegaΩ.
Solution.

Recall the Wirtinger derivatives:

∂f∂z=12(∂f∂x−i∂f∂y)∂f∂z‾=12(∂f∂x+i∂f∂y).\begin{aligned} \pder{f}{z} &= \frac{1}{2}\p{\pder{f}{x} - i\pder{f}{y}} \\ \pder{f}{\conj{z}} &= \frac{1}{2}\p{\pder{f}{x} + i\pder{f}{y}}. \end{aligned}∂z∂f​∂z∂f​​=21​(∂x∂f​−i∂y∂f​)=21​(∂x∂f​+i∂y∂f​).​

From a quick calculation,

∂2f∂z∂z‾=∂2f∂z‾∂z=Δf4.\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial z \partial \conj{z}} = \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial \conj{z} \partial z} = \frac{\Delta{f}}{4}.∂z∂z∂2f​=∂z∂z∂2f​=4Δf​.

where Δ\DeltaΔ is the Laplacian. By assumption on fff, we have

∂2f∂z‾∂z=0and∂2f2∂z‾∂z=0\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial \conj{z} \partial z} = 0 \quad\text{and}\quad \frac{\partial^2 f^2}{\partial \conj{z} \partial z} = 0∂z∂z∂2f​=0and∂z∂z∂2f2​=0

Since the Wirtinger derivatives are derivations, we have

∂f2∂z=2f∂f∂z  ⟹  ∂2f2∂z‾∂z=2∂f∂z‾∂f∂z+2f∂2f∂z‾∂z=2∂f∂z‾∂f∂z.\begin{aligned} \pder{f^2}{z} = 2f \pder{f}{z} \implies \frac{\partial^2 f^2}{\partial \conj{z} \partial z} &= 2\pder{f}{\conj{z}} \pder{f}{z} + 2f \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial \conj{z} \partial z} \\ &= 2\pder{f}{\conj{z}} \pder{f}{z}. \end{aligned}∂z∂f2​=2f∂z∂f​⟹∂z∂z∂2f2​​=2∂z∂f​∂z∂f​+2f∂z∂z∂2f​=2∂z∂f​∂z∂f​.​

Since the left-hand side vanishes, we are left with

∂f∂z‾∂f∂z=0.\pder{f}{\conj{z}} \pder{f}{z} = 0.∂z∂f​∂z∂f​=0.

Now suppose fff is not holomorphic. In particular, fff is harmonic hence C1C^1C1, which implies that fff does not satisfy the Cauchy-Riemann equations everywhere on Ω\OmegaΩ. Thus, there exists z0∈Ωz_0 \in \Omegaz0​∈Ω such that ∂f∂z‾(z0)≠0\pder{f}{\conj{z}}\p{z_0} \neq 0∂z∂f​(z0​)=0. By continuity, this means that ∂f∂z‾≠0\pder{f}{\conj{z}} \neq 0∂z∂f​=0 on a neighborhood of z0z_0z0​. By the equation above, this implies that ∂f∂z\pder{f}{z}∂z∂f​ vanishes on a non-empty open set. Since Ω\OmegaΩ is connected and ∂f∂z\pder{f}{z}∂z∂f​ is harmonic, ∂f∂z\pder{f}{z}∂z∂f​ is identically 000. Hence,

0=∂f∂z‾=12(∂f∂x‾+i∂f∂y‾)=12(∂f‾∂x+i∂f‾∂y)=∂f‾∂z‾,0 = \conj{\pder{f}{z}} = \frac{1}{2} \p{\conj{\pder{f}{x}} + i\conj{\pder{f}{y}}} = \frac{1}{2} \p{\pder{\conj{f}}{x} + i\pder{\conj{f}}{y}} = \pder{\conj{f}}{\conj{z}},0=∂z∂f​​=21​(∂x∂f​​+i∂y∂f​​)=21​(∂x∂f​​+i∂y∂f​​)=∂z∂f​​,

so f‾\conj{f}f​ satisfies the Cauchy-Riemann equations, hence holomorphic.
